[The finding of asymptomatic infections with the epidemic strain, as
discussed in the posting, can expand the epidemiological potential of
transmission of this pathogen. More information regarding the rate of
asymptomatic infection is needed to assess this phenomenon. - Mod.LL]

******
[3] Questions
Date: Wed 13 Jul 2011
Source: Roger Feldman <feldmanmail@aol.com> [edited]


While looking at fenugreek seeds, and their culinary and other uses,
it appears that there are some seeds which are used for specific
purposes, like false maple syrup, some seeds which have culinary uses,
like curry powder, and then, some seeds used for sprouting. If
somebody has contact with those who know about fenugreek seed
production, and the countries which produce them, and then know what
percent of production is used for sprouts, it would add something
useful for those of us who see seed packets on the shelves of garden
stores, or wonder which products (curry powder, and other mixed spice
powders, false maple syrup, and other things) use fenugreek seeds.

As a 2nd question, relating to the size of the infectious dose and
severity of disease, I wonder if the dose from sprouted fenugreek
seeds is massively greater than the dose of _E. coli_ O157:H7 in
undercooked hamburger patties. I only ask because people use the word
virulence as if the only variable involved is the organism. What if
seed-generated disease has a generally different magnitude of dose
than that found with other vehicles?

--
Roger Feldman
<feldmanmail@aol.com>

[ProMED-mail always welcomes Dr Feldman's comments and questions.
More information regarding these issues and many others are needed and
hopefully will be forthcoming. - Mod.LL]
